# Compliance

## What is OSCAL?

The Open Security Controls Assessment Language (OSCAL) is a NIST-standardized,
machine-readable format for expressing security and compliance information.
Version 1.2.1 is the current stable release. By storing compliance posture as
structured JSON alongside your source code, every control mapping is versioned,
diffable, and auditable in the same pull-request workflow used for all other
changes.

Technology Radar v33 (ThoughtWorks) lists OSCAL in the **Adopt** ring for
continuous compliance, recognising that declarative control mapping is now a
production-grade practice for regulated industries.

## Why continuous compliance matters

Traditional point-in-time audits leave gaps between evidence capture and the
actual state of the system. Continuous compliance closes that gap by:

- Expressing every security control as code that lives next to the feature it
  protects.
- Running automated evidence collection in CI alongside tests and SBOM
  generation.
- Producing a tamper-evident audit trail via signed commits and provenance
  attestations.

## The OSCAL sidecar (`docs/oscal/component-definition.json`)

The companion JSON file in `docs/oscal/` is a minimal OSCAL 1.2.1
component-definition. It maps the repository-level controls listed below to
NIST SP 800-53 Rev 5 baseline references.

| Repository control | OSCAL implemented-requirement | NIST 800-53 Rev 5 |
|---|---|---|
| Dependency deny list (`.claude/settings.local.json` `denyList`) | SA-12 — Supply Chain Protection | SA-12 |
| Secret scanning (GitHub Advanced Security / gitleaks) | SI-12 — Information Management | SI-12 |
| Commit signing (GPG / SSH sigstore) | CM-9 — Configuration Management Plan | CM-9 |
| SBOM generation (CycloneDX / SPDX in CI) | SA-12 — Supply Chain Protection | SA-12 |
| Branch protection (required reviews, status checks) | CM-3 — Configuration Change Control | CM-3 |

## Maintaining this file

> **Action required — UUID placeholders**
>
> Every UUID in `docs/oscal/component-definition.json` is set to
> `00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000`. All four UUID levels must be
> replaced with real v4 UUIDs before submitting to an auditor or importing
> into a GRC tool:
>
> - `component-definition.uuid`
> - `components[].uuid`
> - `control-implementations[].uuid`
> - `implemented-requirements[].uuid`
>
> Generate a UUID with:
>
> ```js
> node -e "console.log(crypto.randomUUID())"
> ```

Update `metadata.last-modified` to the current ISO-8601 UTC timestamp
(format: `2026-04-23T00:00:00Z`) whenever you add or remove a control
mapping, and increment `metadata.version` following semantic versioning.
